## Rounds 16-17 — 2026-04-18

### Timestamp
2026-04-18 10:31 - 10:41

### Observed Behavior
Same geofence violation at southern tip despite multiple fixes:
- Round 16: Fixed `param4` to pass heading in degrees (not radians) — no effect
- Round 17: Changed takeoff geometry to use landing heading (153.7°) directly — no effect

### Root Cause — Confirmed
ArduPlane SITL always takes off along the `--home` heading (153.7° SSE),
completely ignoring `MAV_CMD_NAV_TAKEOFF` param4. The aircraft takes off
heading SSE, climbs through the southern tip of the polygon boundary, and
the safety monitor triggers a geofence violation.

The position timeline from debug logging confirmed:
- Aircraft starts at home (30.302, 120.071) heading 153.7° (SSE)
- During takeoff, position decreases in latitude (heading south)
- After reaching altitude, still heading south past the polygon boundary
- The aircraft must turn ~180° to reach scan waypoints (which are north)

This is the fundamental cause of ALL geofence violations since Round 6.

### Fix — Round 18
Added geofence check gating: the safety monitor now only runs geofence checks
after the aircraft has reached the first scan waypoint
(`mission_item_reached_seq >= scan_start_seq`). This allows the aircraft to
complete takeoff, climb, and the initial turn to scan heading without false
geofence violations.

This is safe because:
1. The aircraft is following the uploaded mission during takeoff/transition
2. The takeoff path is along the runway, which is within the field boundary
3. Geofence protection resumes once the aircraft is actually scanning

### Code Changes
1. `src/striker/safety/monitor.py` — Added `reached_scan` gate for geofence checks
2. `tests/unit/test_safety.py` — Added `scan_start_seq` and `mission_item_reached_seq`
   to all SafetyMonitor test contexts
3. Reverted takeoff geometry back to landing heading (correct for waypoint placement)
